Problem set 4

Laura

2016-04-17

Overview

For this problem set you will need to analyze some ChIP-seq data to identify CTCF.

Workflow

Create a run.sh file that runs the entire workflow (or as much as possible). Check.

Alignment

Align FASTQ data to the human genome with bowtie2. There are two files in the data/ directory:

data/factorx.chr1.fq.gz
data/hg19.chr1.fa.gz

First build a bowtie2 index with bowtie2-build and use bowtie2 and samtools to align the reads to the index.

The output of the alignment step is a sorted BAM file.

Create bedGraph

Create a bedGraph file from the sorted BAM files. Use the bedGraphToBigWig utility and the hg19.chrom.size file in the data/ directory.

Create a track in the UCSC browser

  1. Create a branch in your forked repository called gh-pages:
$ git branch gh-pages
$ git push origin gh-pages
  1. Go to the browser and add a “custom track” in the hg19 genome build. your trackline should look something like this (all on one line):
track type=bigWig bigDataUrl="http://lkwhite.github.io/problem-set-4/data/output.bw" color=255,0,0 visiblity=full name='chip data' description='unknown tf'

Peak calling

Call peaks from the bedGraph data using MACS2.

Generate motifs from the peak calls

  1. Use these peak calls to collect FASTA sequences with bedtools getfasta.

  2. Derive motifs from the FASTA sequences with meme.

# if you get an error about "max size" add -maxsize 1000000
$ meme <FASTA file> -nmotifs 1 -maxw 20 -minw 8 -dna
  1. Extract the motif from the meme.txt output and use TOMTOM to identify the motif match. You can use the meme-get-motif to extract the first motif from the file:
meme-get-motif -id 1 < meme.txt

Copy the numeric matrix into the the search box on the tomtom site and report which motif it matches.
